						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">qbradq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Lidnariq,<br /><br />I am not quite sure I understood your comments. I was thinking of using Flash ROMs, not EEPROMs. You can get a 1MB serial Flash ROM for $1.61 USD at Mouser. An 8MB chip is $3.71, and a 16MB chip is $7.18. I seriously doubt anyone will find a use for 16MB on an NES project, unless it's a UNROM pirate cart :D</div>AFAIK, flash ROMs are NOR EEPROMs... The pricing I saw on digikey was pretty awful -- ~$10 for a 8MB one. That said, I don't see a 5V-compatible flash rom on mouser for a sane price...
<br />
<br />Using something like compactflash (or any other parallel-bus flash) has the advantage that cpu-based reading isn't even slower. The big advantage to using something like CF (or SD or whatever) is that you can copy larger content using a card reader. (The downside is you now have to reimplement FAT)
<br />
<br />
<br />Tangenting, I've recently had this silly idea of adding a CDROM drive to the expansion port of the NES, much like the PC-Engine's CDROM. Same problem, same approximately-FDS, but with streaming audio from disk.</div>

